<gtr:id>EC64A8D3-FEAE-4D4E-80AB-6A26FBB4EA0C</gtr:id><gtr:title>The ties that diffuse? Scrutinising the role of dyadic linkages in cross-national environmental spillovers</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Research Grant</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/F03671X/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>Is globalisation good for the environment? One possible way in which globalization might contribute to sustainability at the domestic level is by facilitating the diffusion of more environmentally-sound technologies, organisational practices and performances from more environmentally-progressive countries to less environmentally-progressive ones. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>The over-arching aim of this research project is to examine the extent to which different forms of interconnection between countries contribute to such positive cross-national environmental spillovers. The project makes use of statistical techniques - known as spatial econometrics - which allow researchers to determine whether characteristics in one country &amp;quot;spillover&amp;quot; (that is, diffuse) to others via international contact. Two broad sets of environmental spillover are examined by the project:&lt;/p>

&lt;ul>
 

 &lt;li>environmental innovations such as environmentally-sound technologies, private environmental codes and environmental regulations;&lt;/li>

 &lt;li>actual levels of environmental performance such as carbon-intensity.&lt;/li>
&lt;/ul>

&lt;p>In order to provide a more sophisticated understanding of the role of globalisation, five different international linkages are investigated: trade, investment, telecommunications, diaspora and travel. Data for all five forms of linkage will be dyadic in nature, allowing the researchers to undertake a more geographically disaggregated analysis of the influence of international interconnections.&lt;/p>

